text_retweet:
#repost from @khadija_gbla with @regram.app ... addressing different types of violence against women. â€œviolence against women takes many forms, and occurs in various settings. different types of violence are not mutually exclusive, and women may experience more than one form of violence perpetrated by the same person. it is important to acknowledge that not all forms of violence fit conventional understandings of domestic and family violence, and that tackling violence against women must be sensitive to the variety of experiences of victim/survivors.

sexual violence remains subsumed under the definition of domestic and family violence, which contributes to the invisibility of this issue. while the #metoo movement has highlighted the prevalence of experiences of sexual violence, there is much to be done in giving greater prioritisation and visibility to this gross human rights violation in the policy space. an integrated approach for the prevention of and responses to sexual violence, including comprehensive sexuality education, and education about gender and respectful relationships. law reform and policy development should focus on measures to enhance safe mechanisms of disclosure, promote reporting and evidence collection, and challenge harmful community, police and judicial attitudes towards sexual violence.

other forms of violence against women that are excluded from the focus on a conventional understanding of domestic and family violence include trafficking and sexual exploitation, early and forced marriage, dowry abuse, and labour, domestic and/or sexual servitude. responses to these forms of violence must be co-designed with diverse communities and groups, and ensure access to services no matter whether there is an intention to press charges or not. manifestations of violence such as reproductive coercion, forced sterilisation of women with disability, and medically unnecessary procedures on intersex infants and children need to be within the scope of efforts to end violence against women.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
this is what a ptsd breakthrough looks like. 
7 years ago i stopped driving. i was 17 trying to get my licence. at first i blamed it on college; i moved out of town during the time i was learning, freshman weren't allowed to have cars on campus. but as the years went on i never pursued getting a car or getting my licence. 
7 years ago i was sexually assaulted by my driving instructor. he was a grown man in his forties and he took advantage of a naive girl. i secretly didn't want to pursue driving because i didn't want to be brought back to that place. before i was assaulted i loved driving; i was a little paranoid with my bpd and mood swing/dissociation, but it was relaxing for me. .
tonight i was supposed to go out and have a girl's night with one of my son's aunts. it was getting late when we got together and we didn't feel like doing much so she offered to take me pokÃ©mon hunting (we're avid #pokemongo players, there's not much else to do when you're sober in this town). when we got in the car she offered to let me drive. my heart was racing, something in my gut felt like i was ready and she was the right person to trust this with. .
i drove around an empty parking lot a thousand times, practiced parking and pulling up to the curb, and even drove up to 35 mph on the main road. it doesn't sound like a lot for someone who turns 25 next weekend, but this was a huge step for me. .
i feel like i can breathe again...a little manic, but free. i washed my face tonight, picked out my outfit for my trip to the city tomorrow, and i'm going to bed without feeling suicidal. these are big moves for me. .
now let's hope this energy flow lasts. here's to breaking the cycle and facing your demons. .
.
.

in many cases, self-esteem and domestic violence go hand in hand. low self-esteem can be brought on by a variety of factors and can be a serious issue for women (and men) who are victims of domestic violence.

contrary to what many believe, domestic violence is not just about physical violence. it can also include sexual abuse, emotional abuse, financial abuse, and stalking. basically, domestic violence offenders always feel the need to be in control of their victims. the less in control an offender feels, the more they want to hurt others.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
last night i went on a date with someone who isnâ€™t my wife! i took our five year old daughter out for the evening. she wore one of her favourite dresses, i put on a shirt (pretty dressed up for me). i bought her flowers and we went out for dinner and to enjoy the christmas lights of regent street. 
we played games (eye spy and rock, paper, scissors mostly), tried to identify the animals in nevaehâ€™s â€˜animal pastaâ€™ and sung many songs. 
we had a really fun evening, which was of course the aim. 
there was also another aim. i have a natural instinct as a father, to wrap my kids up in cotton wool to keep them safe. shield them from the world; there is a certain extent to which i do this. however one day, she is going to fly the nest. she will go out into the world and live her own life. if i simply shelter her, i am not properly preparing her to stand on her own two feet. 
i see it as my duty as her dad to demonstrate her worth to her, through the way i treat her. to model the way she should expect all men to behave toward her. to have no question in her own mind of her value. 
this wasnâ€™t a one off. we regularly have â€œdaddy / daughter datesâ€ (this was probably the most fancy so far!) i see myself as a feminist and a â€œmasculinistâ€. the #metoo movement has brought dark, toxic and twisted masculinity into the light. i have made a lifelong commitment to try and show nevaeh (and jj) the strengths and the virtues of a different kind of masculinity. one that doesnâ€™t suppress others but inspires and equips them to live life to its fullest. i aspire to live out those virtues in front of my kids every day! .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
every sunday morning, preachers all over the world insist that you give them your hard-earned money. excuse me, but if the church needs so much money to advance its cause, then why did jesus spend zero time asking people for money? .
.
why didn't jesus charge people for healings then? why didn't jesus charge the crowds to hear him speak like pastors do at conferences today? why didn't jesus take a salary like today's pastors do? why did jesus do everything freely? could it be because the work of god does not depend on money to succeed? .
.
many pastors and preachers don't want you to know this or else they will be out of a job. then, they will have to go out and look for real work like everyone else. many of them don't want to work real jobs. it's too much work. they think they are more important than the regular folk, and a normal job is supposedly below their calling. they want you to go to work and give them donations to pay them a nice salary. they feel entitled to this because of their sense of superiority over those in the pews. they confess jesus as their lord and savior, but they behave nothing like him.
.
.

day 8 | december 02 
sexual consent is  an  agreement to participate in sexual activity between two adults (over the legal age of 18). it is a vital  concept that needs to be understood when it comes to intimate relations between men and women as it must be freely given, reversible, informed, enthusiastic and specific. when there is no consent, it is sexual violation or rape.

if you are forced to have sex against your will, if you say no, asleep, unconscious, under the influence of alcohol or a controlled drug or substance - you cannot give your consent and you have been sexually assaulted.

no means no! hear word! .

text:
nadia murad is an iraqi yazidi woman who survived the worst cruelties ever inflicted on her and her community, the yazidis of iraq. during her ordeal she was held captive and repeatedly gang raped, tortured & beaten. the terrorists organised slave markets for selling off the women & girls and yazidi women were forced to renounce their religion. 
she became an activist after escaping in 2014, campaigning to help put an end to human trafficking and calling on the world to take a tougher line on rape as a weapon of war. 
she is un's first goodwill ambassador for survivors of human trafficking and winner of the nobel peace prize. 
we salute nadia murad for showing and encouraging many women to #standupforyourself

text:
the journey of life is amazing, we travel along it and experience so many things that can be positive and negative... the most important aspect is how we deal with those experiences as that is what shapes us in our own story.

i for one do not regret anything that has happened on my journey, everything has been a learning curve that has helped me grow and become the person i am today and i am so so so grateful for that as i have lived and learnt and continue to live and learn. i am the embodiment of love and feel blessed for that realisation.

whoever is in my life is meant to be and the relationships that i have right now amaze me and are pure and loving, whoever is no longer in my life also amaze me as i have learnt so much from them and am happy that they came into my life taught me and i choose to remove them .

love your journey and just be as that will serve you to the next level.

#jointfamilyabusesurvivor #sexualabusesurvior #metoo #survioroflife #timetotalk #selflove #reiki #inspiration  #lightoflife #selflovereiki #lightworker #grateful #universe #payitforward

text:
the irony of depression is that the more depressed you feel, the more you want to be alone. the more alone you feel, the more depressed you become.
â–â–â–
people often ask me how i overcame depression. first off, much like an eating disorder, i donâ€™t think iâ€™ll ever overcome it. itâ€™s always around the corner and it especially comes up whenever i feel like iâ€™m failing.
â–â–â–
however, the one thing i can say that has helped more than anything in the word is this: connecting. no - not connecting through messages or texts, i mean making the scary step and saying â€œyesâ€ to that coffee catch up or â€œyesâ€ to that dinner party where you donâ€™t know anyone other than the host.
â–â–â–
when jen from @moderndaywoman asked me what i want to achieve with what iâ€™m doing - it was a really simple answer; i said â€œthisâ€ (and pointed to her then myself). iâ€™ve seen the magic that a simple connection can make. it can break down shame and create a level of confidence you would never expect, and certainly better than even the best rx thatâ€™s out there.
â–â–â–
so to everyone out there who is looking to beat depression, anxiety, an eating disorder or anything in between, know this: you are not alone in how you feel. and the sooner you can reach out to someone you trust and say â€œme tooâ€, the closer you will be to living the kind of future you deserve to live.
â–â–â–
written only with love and kindness, dr kat x

text: do you know how big the gender gap is in science, technology, engineering and maths (stem)? women only make up 14.4% of all people working in stem in the u.k. it has been shown that the cultural effects of attributing science subjects to boys and humanities to girls from a young age are a major factor in causing this divide. women earn nearly 1/3 less than men within a year of completing a phd in stem. have a look at www.stem.org.uk for the work being done to inspire a new generation of young women to go into the field. #womenkind

text:
zelda perkins is the former assistant of harvey weinstein and was one of the first women to attempt legal action against the producer while working at miramax in the late 1990s. silenced by a gagging order, she has since spoken out, instigating  a parliamentary inquiry into the unethical nature of non-disclosure agreements.
ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§
breaking her nda in 2017 in the midst of the #metoo movement, perkins' campaign reveals that nda's are used far too often by wealthy and powerful men as a way to cover up their crimes, often including sexual misconduct, assault and rape. at the age of 23, while at the venice film festival, perkins confronted weinstein after he had attempted to rape one of her colleagues, (he had previously made unwanted advances towards perkins as well). of course, weinstein denied all of their accusations, and shortly after, the two women quit their jobs and spoke to solicitors - this was at least 20 years ago. but her lawyer, unconvinced theyâ€™d be able to win a case against miramax and disney (also weinsteinâ€™s company), urged perkinsâ€™ to take the nda, which offered her Â£125,000 (this nda can be viewed online). perkins had to quit the film industry after she was then blacklisted by weinstein. she was not even able to have a copy of the nda, and neither woman was allowed to speak to a therapist. although perkins received a lot of money from the agreement, it has to be remembered that the money was a small amount to weinstein, but a large sum for perkins - an example of how money and influence can silence information that should be public knowledge. thereâ€™s a clear power imbalance, one that allowed weinstein to repeat his misconduct over and over again and bully women into accepting a gagging order rather than speaking out. ~~~
speaking to emily maitlis on @bbc newsnight, perkins explained how the legal system had no way of protecting them and quashed their voices. she explains: 'the problem with the nda is that it has been weaponised by powerful people and by lawyers. we need to have a framework where people can work safely and where there is recourse when these individuals abuse power.'

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

according to the report published in the hans india, this incident took place near balaram krishna puram, krishna district. before making an attempt to rape the girl, they tied her beau to a tree. as per the details of the case, the youths followed the lovers who on the bike. when the couple reached subabul farm, the youths tried to rape the girl. however, when passerby rushed to the spot, the youths managed to escape.

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

despite many stringent laws and awareness movements such as #metoo, it seems that women are not completely safe yet. in a shameful incident, two youths made an attempt to rape a girl in front of her beau.
according to the report published in the hans india, this incident took place near balaram krishna puram, krishna district. before making an attempt to rape the girl, they tied her beau to a tree. as per the details of the case, the youths followed the lovers who on the bike. when the couple reached subabul farm, the youths tried to rape the girl. however, when passerby rushed to the spot, the youths managed to escape.

translation:

in a world where every year on 1st december, everyone celebrates world aids day, ngo jeevan arth foundation thinks that the way people in the country donâ€™t know about hiv/aids and the way there is a lack of awareness, we feel that we need to do efforts everyday to make an awareness amongst our people.

on one side, people around the globe raise their voices, pick posters and take out rallies for hiv/aids awareness. meanwhile on the other side, people in our country find it wrong to talk about such issues.

they donâ€™t feel like addressing such issues. whenever someone wants to talk about this topic or someone is talking on such a topic, theyâ€™re hushed and asked to lower their voices. as if, itâ€™s a taboo to talk about hiv and aids.

people find it uncomfortable to talk about hiv and this makes us more vulnerable to such diseases.

ngo jeevan arth foundation thinks that itâ€™s time we did something on this.

text:
âš ï¸cringe alert, lolâš ï¸ i found a photo gallery yesterday i hadn't been able to access for yearsss. i forgot nearly every single photo had even been taken! they're full of more cringe, more emo than 2007 myspace even knew what to do with, lol, but this is more than just a trip down memory lane.
.
i've been wrestling a lot w/ identity -- who am i, what's my voice, who's my community, is who i am dictated by what i know about me or what's reflected back to me in how others relate to and interact w/ me? so many questions after a year of my life and body radically shifting beneath my feet. all of these photos were from age 18-19, just one year -- and as you can see i lived a hundred lifetimes in that time. fighting for the safety to be herself. a tomboy badass, who despised being a girl in every possible way, trapped in a world demanding nothing but delicate, feminine, pretty, christian, driven, pure. that dissonance amplified the agony and made the plunges into the darkness all the more drastic. masking as a hyperfeminine, gentle girl only reminded me of the abuse given to me bc of both those very qualities. ..but exploring the alternative was dangerous, unsafe, put a target on my back. at this point i was clawing to get out; i broke. so, i tried.
.
now, i'm trying to find me again. a queer, adrogynous creative; an artist. i'm edgy, tough, a bit of a bamf. i also live and breathe compassion, empathy, nurture, love. i'm a scientist, a realist, still feel like an athlete inside. i'm an educator, an advocate, owner of a very broken body. i'm sick. i'm also a survivor, who's felt pure unimaginable evil and come out alive. i'm also so many things no one even knows about, but they're still in there. in me.
.
i haven't found me fully again, it'll be awhile. but, it makes it hard to laugh too hard at this mess of a kidd above. on one hand, she feels like an alien to me. someone i don't know and have never met in my life. but i also feel so close to her in that brutal place where you're trying to find yourself but trauma keeps changing who you are before you've even gotten to know the last girl. ..it's rough.
.
i hope we both get there. until then, enjoy the  laughs.
.

text:
seriously? 
she was charged with 'inciting debauchery'. give us a break. she was attending an award ceremony, and she wore a dress that showed a bit of body. seriously dudes. get a grip. at most she was inciting publicity for her movies. -
when oh when will all of these antiquated, outdated, way too often enshrined in religious precepts, designed to diminish women, systems of thought and practice be wiped off the face of the earth?
-
i know this is such a smaller news issue than the much much much larger issue of millions of women and girls experiencing violence or constraints because of their gender in every country every day. but it is symptomatic. and illustrates how embedded the mental models of control of women are.
-
so in fact, there is inciting to be done. 
let's consciously incite women's rights change work! 
the work of our own agency, of freeing up mindsets, of living without the daily background worry of safety, of changing outdated legal systems of inequity, of achieving equal pay for same work, of having full control of what we do with and to our bodies without interference from governments, of continuing to gain equal rights in realm after realm after realm. 
and yes, of even including in our mission the right to wear whatever trendy or silly outfit we damn well please without having to worry about the behavioral or ethical choices of others. and even, if we are to of inciting consensual debauchery. -
#changemakers #equalrights #feminist #equalpay #womensrights #womenagentsofchange #timesup #metoo #equality

text:
a woman's perspective // hawick // tuesday 4th december
.
i've been asked to speak in the scottish borders this coming tuesday as part of the annual 16 days of activism event. each year, organisations across the globe host events to raise awareness of gender-based violence. as some of the women in my series nevertheless, she persisted have been affected by various forms of gendered abuse (child, sexual and domestic), i have been asked to share stories from the series and talk about what i have learned from all 25 women.
.
the talk is free and open to all. the event will run from 11am-3pm with my talk starting at noon. books will be available to purchase on the day for Â£5.
.
please share with all your friends in the borders!
.

hi to anyone who stumbled across this page!! iâ€™m creating this page to help myself connect more with others during my own journey. a little information about me: â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”ğŸƒ i have experienced sexual assault twice in my life. once as a child by a relative and once in college. iâ€™m in the process of working through it with my therapist and pursuing emdr in january ğŸ™ŒğŸ™Œ â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”ğŸƒ the single element that has helped me the most (so far) is connection with others and sharing my story (thus why i created this page). also, maybe if i can help anyone else through my journey, that would be very meaningful for me.
â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”ğŸƒ iâ€™m the first to admit that #traumawork is kind of the worst, but certainly the only way out is through.

text:
your silence speaks volumes, 
i hear every word you don't say. 
your silence is deadly, 
it killed my love for you. 
your silence filled me with sadness, 
i'll never be the same. 
your silence is reckless, 
you know not what you do. 
your silence, it broke me,
my heart is torn in two.

your silence,
it's over. -crg

#poem #myheart #truth #love #life #poetry #heal #story #metoo #abuse #rape #recover #my #art #forgive

text:
on one of my remaining nights in lisbon, i had some unfinished business to take care of.  i dodged out into the city, and dove into the cloudy, rainy night and headed to the waterâ€¦.to gather rocks. rocks to mark with memories, and awareness. .
.
i love tradition. i crave closure. i seek ways to â€œmarkâ€ a time and place, and memories.  these rocks will serve me well. they are resting by the ocean.
.
.
lisbonâ€™s beauty offered me a place to let go of some stuff that has been reflecting back at me, from when trauma first occurred.  we all have these external happenings that begin to engage our deepest need for affirmation and sacred love, but instead become harmful reminders that what was done somehow was a reflection of our worth (lie). .
.
i learned self-hate by listening to the message of the harm done to me and all the complexities that came with it. trauma does not teach you that what was done to you was wrong.  it teaches you that it somehow was your fault, or that you somehow invited it in. .
.
i can safely say, that i have become my biggest advocate. i am constantly learning new ways to slow down, connect and be aware of the reality of what is going on inside of me, and what needs to happen next to further the growth. .
.
i sat and reflected on much of those inner messages that i need to let go of. they included constant thoughts that haunt me, and areas of my life that i need to leave behind. .
.
on my last evening in portugal, i wondered to the ocean at sunset, rocks in hand. each marked with the crippling messages or actions that have continually paused further growth. .
.
one by one, while the sunset posed as the backdrop, i tossed the rocks and their messages in the ocean... to celebrate that i no longer have a place for them. .
.
if this resonates with you, then please grab your rocks. mark them, and know that you have permission to move towards the places where you find yourself adored, cherished, and loved in the most sacred waysâ€¦toss the rocks far from youâ€¦. hold your hunger for genuine desire in a new light without those old messages, and know you are not and never have been alone in your search for belonging safe and sacredâ€¦

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
big tw for #transphobia #sexism and rape talk.

sometimes it's too painful to tell our own stories--but it's even more painful to be erased from their tellings. it was a different time when @hilaryswank was casted in #boysdontcry , the film and true story of #brandonteena hit home for me as a trans boy, a rape survivor, a midwesterner, as someone who has had life on the line, as someone who has been called on the phone just to be called faggot. moving forward, if you're gonna better and kill us on screen, at least hire the people who have survived it all. it may not be the 90s anymore, but many of us, especially those from/in #trumpsamerica , still follow brandon's life trajectory until the end.

to the right is a #remixed scene from the film holding my own pain and the pain of my community. big love to @thestudioact and @bradcalcaterra for your caring direction of the piece, and @joslyn.defreece for going there with the most understanding anyone could ever have. big love to the actors & creatives who are working on this very thing in big ways right now; we need you ğŸ’œğŸ’œğŸ’œ, @loganrozos @tracelysette

text:
despite the fact that ethlyne clair (born november 23, 1904) was probably one of the most beautiful women ever to grace the screen during the late 1920s/early 1930s, she never became a star.
â€¢
ethlyne made her break for stardom after winning a beauty contest in her home town of talladega, alabama, and headed to new york to find work as an extra (her first role of note was in sandra (1924) starring barbara la marr). â€¢
â€¢
in hollywood, she signed a contract with universal; appearing in a handful of comedies shorts, including the newlyweds, followed by a spate of westerns opposite hoot gibson. â€¢
â€¢
in 1928, she married her agent, richard lonsdale hinshaw, in mexico. it was an unhappy union; she later revealed he forced her into marriage at gunpoint. her career also waned, after playing second fiddle to rex, the wonder horse, she left universal, and freelanced. it was pathÃ©, representing a variety of independent film studios, who nominated her as one of the years wampas baby stars of 1929. the accolade kept her in the press; she was also one of hollywoodâ€™s first stars to launch her own beauty care range. it was this which brought her to the attention of ernest westmore, of the hollywood make-up dynasty.
â€¢
divorced from her husband, her marriage to ernest wasnâ€™t without drama; when at their wedding, his first wife showed up with their daughter, muriel, dressed in rags to highlight the state of poverty ernest had left them in. ernest in turn flew at photographers; got into a brawl and was arrested. as his career flourished, ethlyneâ€™s went into a deep decline; her temporary contract with warner bros. had expired and she was out of work. later, in 1991, she claimed that mogul daryl zanuck ruined her career after she refused his sexual advances. â€¢
â€¢
by 1934, with her film career over, she tried her hand on the stage with limited results. instead, divorced from ernest, she married again, to a second-hand car salesman, and retired to raise her family. she died in february 1996, aged 91.
â€¢
â€¢

text:
day 2 #dogoodthischristmas 
who am i? and what is unique about me? it is not easy to unravel these layers, but so important for our mental well-being. this is what we focussed on in our last #femchats session. it was an inspiring evening talking about feminism, feminist art, why we are all really feminists, gender equality, and how art can be used not only for mindfulness but self-expression and activism. so empowering to have space and time to share ideas, books, and be creative. i felt thoughtful but also so optimistic. .
.
//

text:
2 1/2 years ago i was raped...
.
i was 14
and in a relationship with an abusive man
he yelled at me
he threatened me
i was horrified of him
sex was a given. i didn't have an option
i was too scared to leave
too scared to be alone
.
he told me he'd kill himself if i left
he wouldn't let me go out with my friends
he completely controlled my life in every aspect
.
for years i dealt with panic attacks, flashbacks, nightmares, extreme anxiety, and self harm
.
but now, 2 1/2 years later i'm finally ready to talk about it
about the thing that scarred me forever
because i want to tell you, you're not alone
and it doesn't have to be like this
you can get out
you can have healthy, happy relationships
you can heal
.
emdr saved my life and i'm no longer diagnosed or dealing with ptsd, but the rape and the relationship changed my life forever
.
it took years for me to heal. to see that this has a purposes
and this is why now i will be including finding and growing healthy relationships in my coaching
because i've been there, and i want to help you get out of it
i want to help you see the purpose. to see the light. to heal. to grow.
.
if you who also have been sexually assulted or in a toxic relationship, i want you to know, there's a light on the other end, even if you can't see it right now. i want you to know you're not alone. thousands of women stand by you, including me. together we will heal. together we will grow. together we will change the world
.
finding and growing healthy relationships will now be included in my coaching, because it doesn't have to be like this. i want to help you find and grow healthy relationships and get out of the toxic ones
.
you are not alone
i see you
i feel you
i believe you
#metoo

text:
i'll be in the mountains in utah this week for a healing retreat. the farthest west i've been is des moines, iowa.

this retreat is specifically for women who are survivors of childhood sexual abuse. i get to learn more ways to help me heal. from tai chi to cooking. i might even get a makeover?! it's pretty exciting but surreal!

because it's a retreat for survivors, safety is everything so i won't be sharing my journey while i'm there. i'll take pics and talk more about it once i'm back home. but i just wanted to share my excitement and nervousness with you all. i've never done anything like this but i'm open. i'm ready.

healing is a never ending journey for me. a cyclical one that rolls over the highs and the lows, always moving forward.

this stunning picture is by my talented friend @parkerspics313 and my makeup is done by the one and only @lybartistryofficial who both generously gave me their time, energy and love just to make my vision project journey come to life. a self reflection on healing from my traumas. i wrote a blog post on it back in march - website link in bio.

well this post is long as hell. i'm so grateful for all of you always supporting me! i can't wait to learn and grow. i hope to come back renewed and empowered to continue my work inside and out!

happy sunday if you made it this far!

#healingispossible #healingjourney #metoo #believesurvivors #iamasurvivor #grateful #mindbodysoul #spiritualjourney

well this post is long as hell. i am so grateful for all of you always suppoing me! i can not wait to learn and grow. i hope to come back renewed and empowered to continue my work inside and out!

happy sunday if you made it this far!

rising: east of eden (6/14) by nicholas jones, 28 november 2016. -

you once told me that someone feeling love pains,
is capable of self-degradation in the most unbelievable ways,
and certain liquids gave birth to certain lapses of judgment,
and it seemed as though i found love in the most hopeless places,
maybe thatâ€™s why i write about love all the time,
because i want it more than anything else,

we sat on your couch and stayed up until five,
talking about vintage cars and old hollywood guys,
then you flashed that smile that you so often wear,
whenever you were with me and i never cared,
we watched the sun come up over the clouds,
and then i fell upwards and never came down,
and you put on that same old movie you always played,
east of eden was never too far away,

you were the first man that i ever loved,
fate took its turn and tragedy struck,
so they buried you way out past highway six,
where you taught me how to drive your stick shift,
and i look in the mirror each and everyday,
and iâ€™ve yet to find a part of me that,
hasnâ€™t been touched by you in some way,

so i went back to my bed and laid there still,
and i thought that watching east of eden,
could have brought my head right back to your chest,
and i would have watched it again and again,
without hesitation - because you were just the best,
the academy award for the most beautiful mess,
because all of the great and precious things in this world are lonely,

your iconic gaze gave way to faith that someday,
iâ€™d love you in a special way - two hearts entombed,
in shallow graves for fire signs that set the world ablaze,
just east of eden at the intersection of glory days and memory lane. -

text:
rising: kindred spirit (7/14) by nicholas jones, 26 september 2018. -

kindred spirit - canâ€™t you see that iâ€™m laying in your bed,
after spending my whole saturday
running through your head,
you can feel me underneath you and i can feel you deep inside,
kindred spirit - canâ€™t you see that you donâ€™t have to hide from me?

our views of the world have been defined by billions of years,
of evolutionary theory that brought us here,
together - hand in hand - we stand up in defense,
of everything the world has to use against us,

kindred spirit - canâ€™t you see there are no wars to be waged,
that if we can bring two worlds together then we could motivate,
the change we want to see into the actions,
we want to be defined by - but only when kindred spirits learn to fly together. -

text:
rising: lana del rey (8/14) by nicholas jones, 02 october 2018. -

i always listen to bob dylan when i want to feel close to my father,
blood on the tracks - highway 61 - blonde on blonde,
i donâ€™t know all of the words to every song that comes on,
but i do know just enough to be able to sing along,

i always listen to mariah carey when i miss my ex-boyfriend,
all that glitters is gold - he used to say to me,
and i took that spiritually - as if he was going to say,
that whenever i felt lonely - he was never too far away,

i always listen to madonna whenever i feel like i just want to dance,
because if youâ€™ve hung up your dancing shoes - youâ€™ll never have the chance,
to see the world the way it was meant to be seen - a chance to reinvent yourself each day,
and that everyday is a holiday if you open your heart - at the expense of loving someone else,

i listen to maya angelou on repetition - to soothe,
to heal and redirect my attitude towards the human condition,
you are beautiful and you are strong - and if you have faith,
your wings will spread from to sea to sea - wall to wall - face to face,

and i listen to lana del rey all the time - happy or sad,
to remember what iâ€™ve always wanted and what i once had,
because if weâ€™re only born to die - doesnâ€™t it make sense to cling to life,
with someone who you love - who loves you - while you pass the time. -

text:
let's talk recovery. a large part of me has always been frightened by what recovery would look like. one, i was resistant to the idea of needing medication. and, two, i was afraid it would take my personality away. i would be boring, i guess. well, i'm beginning to enter recovery as i am no longer resistant to taking medication  but embracing treatment, four months strong, a new record of consistency for me. and, it's not that recovery takes away your personality but it stabalizes you. it makes things clearer, decisions easier, and puts things in perspective. i think i might like recovery. recovery from all the intertwined obstacles and mental disorders i face might actually be a relief, a breath of fresh air. i share this incredibly personal story to say, don't stand in the way of your own treatment and your own recovery. look honestly at what's holding you back and accept the role you play. it's hard but that's what makes it worth it. .
.
.

text:
today was a big learning day ğŸ™Œ 
about a month ago i was encouraged to race at the masters â€œlast chanceâ€ meet in order to get @mastersswimming top 10 ranking times before the end of the year. i wasnâ€™t sure i wanted to do that again but i entered. i have not trained like i used to, only a couple of times a week....so no expectations were there...just swim...have fun and try to enjoy doing something that i spent my entire life pursuing. i raced, i laughed, i learned to relax, live in the moment, be ok with â€œmy timesâ€ (which were super slow) and just treat the entire 2 days like one giant swim practice ğŸ˜‚ğŸ‰ğŸ’¥ 13 races, 13 medals, relay races, new friends, almost missing 2 of my swims ğŸ˜‚and finishing the meet with 0 best times...but i am #grateful cuz i realized i still love ğŸ’— this sport even though it has given more heart ache, disappointment, politics and #metoo moments in my young coaching career to ever want to go back ğŸ˜¢ but today i feel proud. proud of my relentless commitment to the pursuit of being my best and always aiming to work for my dream of competing in the olympics. i gave 8 quadrennials (32 years) of my life to this sport including hard work, blood-sweat-tears, sacrifice, dedication of body, spirit and soul and i didnâ€™t â€œmake itâ€ ğŸ™€ but what i did do today was finally realize that what i did accomplish over the past 32 years was freaking amazing ğŸ’¥ğŸ’ªğŸ’¦ and that i would give anything to swim my best times again ğŸ˜Œ...i learned that itâ€™s ok to want and to love something and not get it....itâ€™s the same in life and itâ€™s the same with people. you can give and love with all of your heart and not get what you want. ğŸ¤·ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸as long as you are happy with you and what you believe in, you will be ok. so i say this to me and to anyone pursuing a dream or going through doubts or heartache, depression or uncertainty...you are great, beautiful, courageous and a fighter. 
you be you and it will all be ok â¤ï¸ğŸ¤—ğŸ’¦ .
.
.
.

text:
today marks the one year anniversary of the toronto metoo march, which i feel infinitely blessed to have been apart of, along with hundreds of other survivors of assault and abuse. i am forever grateful to hero leader @_alatheacaroline_ for making this life changing day happen, and for all of the astoundingly brave human beings who came out to participate and support a cause that is at the epicenter of my heart. that day we were no longer victims. we were champions.
the event was one of the most beautifully heartbreaking days of my entire life. i cried tears of pain, joy, sorrow, anger, and love for what we were fighting for then, and i am again right now. although this topic covers so many complex and diverse issues, it can be understood simply as an overwhelming fight for freedom.
and even though we have come a long way, the fight is far from being over. there is so much work left to be done and i am not waiting around for someone to stand up and do something. instead i am brimming with excitement to be continuing this movement, and will be coordinating a feminist artist workshop to unite la artists in solidarity for gender equality. we all deserve to live and create art in a city where freedom from sexual harassment and assault is not the exception, but the rule. there will be a luncheon during the first week of january to kick things off and i welcome you to join me. letâ€™s start talking and get moving. letâ€™s empower each other with our own stories of strength, courage and hope to discuss how we can work together to make la a city that thrives off of equality. this is only the beginning of the most magical era of our lifetime and i am ecstatic to be apart of it. there is no better time to be alive than right now. 
#metoo #metoomovement #equality

text: why do i call myself a feminist? because women have a right to their bodies, to their sexuality, to their reproductive choices. because, we are healing, thousands of years of cultural conditioning that affects who we have become, which is so very far from who we are. because being sexy af is not a sin, nothing about our nakedness is shameful and it does not imply consent to be naked. because we are finding our voices healing  and reaching out to co-conspire with our male counterparts who stand with us to seek justice. because we live in a world where women are still murdered for adultery even if it was rape! because the president of the usa can "grab em' by the pussy' like we are play things. because we still victim shame and disbelieve with very limited understanding of the trauma, the ptsd and the absolute fucking courage it takes to actually speak up. because death threats are real in the usa if you do speak up. because death threats were the reason i didn't 30 years ago. because i want to change the landscape of our relationship to our self worth, boundary setting and heal our sexuality. because we are all beautiful and deserving of a life of love, to feel safe, intimate connection and mind-blowing, orgasmic sex.

text:
yesterday, on my way to #ballet class, i got a little shocked when i looked up from my phone and saw an erected penis pointing at my face. i pretended not to be fazed, left the train at the nearest station and then switched to a different compartment. when i got off the train, the flasher also came out from the original compartment and saw me. luckily he didn't follow me and i quickly walked up the escalator. i experienced an aftershock the rest of the day as flashbacks of perverts rubbing on me or showing their weiners when i was a child came back to haunt me. i had to try hard to distract myself to get rid of the disgusting images in my head. focusing 100% during the ballet class really helped me dilute the impact of the shock. but i must say it wasn't an easy process for me.Â 
the fact that this event triggered such an emotional charge in me points to the fact that i had unhealed wounds from the past. what i went through as a child made me believe, falsely, thatÂ it was my fault to look attractive and cause those perverts to target me. for most of my teenage years, i deliberately tried to look very unattractive to avoid attention from men. during those years, i had no one to talk to safely about what i had experienced and so the trauma became internalized and never dealt with. worse still, the childhood traumas made me believe that only ugly guys or perverts were interested in me, deeply affecting my self-esteem and confidence as i grew up to be an adult.Â 
some of my friends have suggested calling the police or the mta officer yesterday. but i was in a very packed train and there were no mta officers onboard. besides, i was determined to get to my destination on time. but even if i had the time, how would i deal with the situation? drag the flasher to the mta booth? call the police? by the time the authorities arrive, the guy would have disappeared. i don't know. safety was at the top of my concern at that point, and i did not want any violent retaliation of any kind to happen to me. so even though i chose to be silent, it was out of self-preservation. tell me, what would you have done in such a situation? i don't have the vocab for calling out for help! #metoo

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

indonesia masih belum memiliki payung hukum yang mengatur jelas dan rinci mengenai jenis-jenis kekerasan seksual yang jumlahnya selalu tinggi setiap tahunnya. karena absennya uu yang memadai dan berpihak pada korban, upaya mencari keadilan untuk korban menjadi sulit dan terbatas. â €â €
ini bukan isu perempuan saja, ini isu kita bersama. mari kita suarakan dan turun bersama 8 desember untuk mendorong pemerintah segera sahkan ruu penghapusan kekerasan seksual!

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

it is unlawful to discriminate against employees because of their sexual orientation, whether someone is lesbian, gay, heterosexual, bisexual or asexual.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
trigger warning 
excerpt from #metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women â€œsince my first rape the summer before my freshman year of college i have had a repetitive thought in my head. i wish that they had killed me instead. â€œi wish that they had killed me instead.â€ because at least then it would have just been done and over with. i wouldnâ€™t live with nightmares and ptsd and all the lifelong trauma that goes along with being raped. being sexually assaulted is that invasive and dehumanizing. like i said above, iâ€™ve lost just about everything that made me who i was before the rapes. everything about me is different. i even laugh different. itâ€™s basically like they killed me anyway. now i often feel just like a shell of a human being.â€
.
.
my latest project is called â€œ#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.â€
i am still collecting stories. submissions will be accepted until december 31, 2018.
if you have a story that you would like to include email me at mchillstromauthor@yahoo.com.
all stories will be listed as anonymous submissions.
the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-sexual harassment -rape/assault -sexual, emotional, or physical abuse
-stalking
-gender discrimination
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well.
through writing my own stories i have found peace and strength.
i hope others will find this as well along with the knowledge that they are not alone.
proceeds from the sales of this collection will be donated to help sexual assault survivors.
.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
how does empowerment mean going around semi nude and allowing people to objectify you? never heard that men come out naked to exert that they are strong or capable or talented... walking around, i noticed some young girls dressed skimpy and passerby men staring at them. this is a 'common' experience which you will hear from many people... so a quick question to all the women, why allow someone to treat you like an object? 
some have become so used to this that it no longer bothers them, but these are the ones who will do candle light march and a #metoo movement when they are actually not respecting themselves  learn to respect yourself and then expect others to respect you !!! leave your experience or thoughts below

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
more details from saptamatrika... the 7 mothers. .
.
about mothers,sisters, daughters and friends- saptmatripa.
manifestations inspire me to attempt to analyze the world i see around me, 
especially as a woman who must make sense, daily 
of injustices in the world. 
to comprehend why we continue to look away when prejudice occurs, 
when sensitivities corrode, or when negative forces are invoked. 
i, therefore, look inwards 
to evoke the energy that is manifest in each one of us
to apply the healing salve of motherhood to a world that needs it. 
for that energy resides in each one of us 
women and men 
crossing all genders 
and it is that i must manifest..
.
.
.

text:
at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like â€˜drain the swampâ€™ or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the â€˜deep stateâ€™ that werenâ€™t necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

jon sharman
the independent

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
it is unlawful to discriminate against employees because of their sexual orientation. 
so how does sexual orientation discrimination appear in the workplace?

direct discrimination is where an employee is unfairly treated by their employer due to their sexual orientation or perceived sexual orientation. 
this includes:
opportunities for promotion and training
changes in employment terms and role responsibilities
differences in pay and benefits for individuals of different sexual orientation
redundancy and dismissal

direct discrimination also includes the recruitment process whereby job seekers are not offered a role based on their sexual orientation or perceived sexual orientation.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
next march, an employment tribunal will decide whether veganism is a "philosophical belief" protected by the equality act 2010.
what is defined as a â€˜beliefâ€™?
this relates to both religious and philosophical belief. philosophical belief is a little trickier to define. it is not an opinion or point of view; rather it is identified under the equality act as genuinely held, clear, logical, convincing and a substantial aspect of human life and behaviour, worthy of respect in democratic society, compatible with human dignity and not conflicting with the fundamental rights of others â€“ i said this was tricky!
humanism, atheism and agnosticism are examples of â€˜beliefsâ€™, but the key takeaway point here is weâ€™re talking about a belief that is â€œnot conflicting with the fundamental rights of othersâ€.
it is also important to note that all protected beliefs are equal; no one belief carries more weight or influence over the other, nor does having no belief.
predictions on the outcome of this test case please....

text:
perseverance
.
keep on going.
keep on fighting.
life is so damn fun and joyful but it can be intense and crazy too.
.
one of the greatest lessons that ironman training has taught me is that of perseverance. the road is long and the fight is sometimes difficult. but we must never ever give up.
.
i have a mantra iâ€™ve always used during races when it gets tough...
.
â€œi didnâ€™t come this far, to simply come this far.â€
.
itâ€™s carried me through the inevitable lows that we all experience racing. and even in moments when quitting seems like the â€œeasyâ€ option.
.
itâ€™s paradoxical to me how much ironman training and races has paralleled my life the past 17 months. and especially now more than ever.
.
i didnâ€™t come this far to come this far. doing the right, ethical and honest thing isnâ€™t always easy. speaking about injustice whether experienced yourself or to others can be scary especially when silencing the victims, manipulation, threats and coercion run rampant in our society. telling the truth, speaking your truth and honoring the truth of those around has never been more vital.
.
i guess i never realized ironman training was actually preparing me for something bigger. giving me the mental and physical fortitude to step into the arena and not back down. i want to live in a society where women arenâ€™t pushed down for speaking their truth and when they are met with betrayal, lies, threats, name calling and those who want them silenced...they persevere. i want to live in a world where i raise my boys to stand up for whatâ€™s right and be brave and courageous enough to stand up for women, their friends and themselves.
.
ironman has taught me the literal meaning of its slogan:
.
â€œanything is possibleâ€
.
when you are walking in the truth, doors open. people enter your life to help and guide you. you have the strength of god, angels and the universe on your side. this i know for sure.
.
so persevere my friends. donâ€™t quit. do the hard thing especially when itâ€™s the right thing. youâ€™ll sleep better at night knowing youâ€™re speaking truth. keep on keeping on. life will throw you curve balls, highs and lows. ride them with grace. everything passes. love and truth alway wins ğŸ–¤ğŸ”¥

text:
healing is a long process. i needed and still need time to heal myself. it's not like a broken bone that you simply wrap in plaster to heal the fracture and put the broken parts together again. you have to heal yourself and put your broken parts back together again by yourself.
the damage controlled me ever since. too afraid to talk about it, too afraid to go somewhere on my own, too many thoughts that i'm not good enough for anything or anyone. but i'm sick of being controlled.
so i started this page to talk about it. i booked flights and accomodation to go to a different country on my own. i keep on telling myself that i am indeed good enough and that people who don't value me can go and fuck themselves!
the damage doesn't control me any longer and you'll be able to get through this as well â™¡
.
.

so i started this page to talk about it. i booked flights and accomodation to go to a different country on my own. i keep on telling myself that i am indeed good enough and that people who do not value me can go and fuck themselves!
the damage does not control me any longer and you'll be able to get through this as well â™¡
.
.

text:
there are hundreds of memes, viral videos, and challenges all over the internet. but through movements like body positivity, mental health awareness, and #metoo, social media has been able to truly impact lives, all over the world.Â herstoryÂ reached out to five young women who are using social media to empower themselves and others

1. arjama bakshi (@shareerspeak), 18, is a student from kolkata, is encouraging body positivity among teenagers and young adults through art and collaborations with other self-love advocates. she believes that we all should embrace our flaws and try our best to be authentically ourselves.

2. kavya shankar (@bodypositivecoach), 28, is a body-positive fitness entrepreneur from bengaluru, who has overcome challenges from body-shaming to sexual harassment. she shares her experiences with her followers, and has built a close-knit online family.

3. neelakshi singh (@plumptopretty), 27, is a body-positive fashion blogger from mumbai, who aims to destigmatise everything that challenges the standards of beauty. she is working towards the day when women's bodies are respected and not body-shamed.

4. leyre garatea (@leyleyleu), 27, is a spanish game designer living in bengaluru. she stands by and supports marginalised communities as much as she can, both online and off. she shares her own struggles with mental health and more, aiming to be as real as possible.

5. vijaya aswani (@spreefirit), 24, is an illustrator based in bengaluru, who hopes that her art makes people smile and feel better. she seeks support among women online, and looks up to those who voice their experiences out loud.

#socialmedia #empoweringwomen
#empowerment #empoweringgirls #bodypositive #bodypositivity #ngo #welfare #feminism #empowering #empoweringothers
